column1: Hint:
Lecture: Lines of latitude and lines of longitude are imaginary lines drawn on some globes and maps. They can help you find places on globes and maps.

Lines of latitude show how far north or south a place is. We use units called degrees to describe how far a place is from the equator. The equator is the line located at 0° latitude. We start counting degrees from there.
Lines north of the equator are labeled N for north. Lines south of the equator are labeled S for south. Lines of latitude are also called parallels because each line is parallel to the equator.

Lines of longitude are also called meridians. They show how far east or west a place is. We use degrees to help describe how far a place is from the prime meridian. The prime meridian is the line located at 0° longitude. Lines west of the prime meridian are labeled W. Lines east of the prime meridian are labeled E. Meridians meet at the north and south poles.
The equator goes all the way around the earth
column2: but the prime meridian is different. It only goes from the North Pole to the South Pole on one side of the earth. On the opposite side of the globe is another special meridian. It is labeled both 180°E and 180°W.

column1: Together
column2: lines of latitude and lines of longitude form a grid. You can use this grid to find the exact location of a place.

column1: Solution: The equator is the line at 0° latitude. It intersects Africa. It does not intersect North America or Australia.
Instruction:

The atomic symbol in a chemical formula may be followed by a small number written lower than the symbol. This number is called a subscript. A subscript is included when the atoms in the elementary substance are bonded to form molecules. The subscript shows how many atoms are in each molecule.
For example
column2: the chemical formula for the elementary substance oxygen
column3: O2
column4: has a subscript of 2. This subscript shows that the atomic symbol O represents two atoms. The elementary substance O2 and the chemical element represented by the atomic symbol O are both named oxygen. So
column5: the formula tells you that each molecule of O2 contains two oxygen atoms.

column1: A compound is represented by a chemical formula that contains multiple atomic symbols.
The chemical elements in a compound are bonded together in a fixed ratio. This ratio is shown in a compound's chemical formula.
For example
column2: in the compound beryllium fluoride
column3: there is one beryllium atom for every two fluorine atoms. So
column4: the ratio of beryllium atoms to fluorine atoms is 1 to 2. This ratio is shown in the chemical formula for beryllium fluoride
column5: BeF2. There is no subscript following the atomic symbol Be because that symbol represents one atom. The subscript 2 follows the atomic symbol F to show that the symbol represents two atoms.

column1: Solution: You can tell whether chloromethane is an elementary substance or a compound by counting the number of atomic symbols in its chemical formula. An atomic symbol consists of either one capital letter or a capital letter followed by one or two lowercase letters.

column3: contains three atomic symbols: C for carbon
column5: and Cl for chlorine. So
column6: the formula tells you that chloromethane is composed of three chemical elements bonded together.

column1: Hint:
Lecture: A strong argument uses valid reasoning and logic in support of a claim. When an argument or claim introduces irrelevant information or misrepresents the issues at hand
column2: it may be committing a logical fallacy. Logical fallacies can hurt a writer's credibility and can lead readers to draw false conclusions.

column1: A logical fallacy may present irrelevant information:
Fallacy | Description
ad hominem | an attack against the person making the argument
column2: rather than the argument itself

column1: appeal to nature | an argument that assumes the natural choice is always the best choice
bandwagon fallacy | an argument that assumes the popular choice is always the best choice
circular reasoning | an argument that supports a claim with the claim itself
guilt by association | an unfair negative association with another person or group that is intended to discredit someone or something
A logical fallacy may misrepresent the issues at hand:
Fallacy | Description
false causation | the assumption that because two things happened together
column2: one caused the other

column1: false dichotomy | an argument that presents only two choices when more options exist
hasty generalization | a broad claim based on too few observations
slippery slope fallacy | the false assumption that a small first step will necessarily lead to extreme consequences
straw man | a misrepresentation of an opponent's position that makes it easier to argue against
Solution: The text argues that a week without rain is evidence that Seattle isn't a rainy city. However
column2: the experience of one week doesn't necessarily reflect longer trends in a place's climate. This illustrates a type of logical fallacy known as a hasty generalization.

The symbol may be followed by a subscript. A subscript is text that is smaller and placed lower than the normal line of text. A subscript is included when the atoms in the elementary substance are bonded to form molecules. The subscript tells you the number of atoms in each molecule.

column2: the chemical formula for the elementary substance oxygen is O2. The formula has a subscript of 2. This subscript tells you that there are two atoms in the molecule represented by this chemical formula.

column1: The chemical element represented by the symbol O is also called oxygen. So
column2: the formula O2 tells you that each molecule of O2 contains two oxygen atoms.

column1: A compound is represented by a chemical formula that contains multiple symbols.
For example
column2: in the compound beryllium fluoride
column3: there is one beryllium atom for every two fluorine atoms. This combination is shown in the compound's chemical formula
column5: the symbol Be represents one beryllium atom. The symbol F followed by the subscript 2 represents two fluorine atoms.

column1: Solution: You can tell whether boron trifluoride is an elementary substance or a compound by counting the number of symbols in its chemical formula. A symbol contains either one capital letter or a capital letter followed by one or two lowercase letters.

column2: the formula tells you that boron trifluoride is made of two chemical elements bonded together.

column1: Hint:

column1: A logical fallacy may present irrelevant information:
Fallacy | Description
ad hominem | an attack against the person making the argument
column2: rather than the argument itself

column1: appeal to nature | an argument that assumes the natural choice is always the best choice
bandwagon fallacy | an argument that assumes the popular choice is always the best choice
circular reasoning | an argument that supports a claim with the claim itself
guilt by association | an unfair negative association with another person or group that is intended to discredit someone or something
A logical fallacy may misrepresent the issues at hand:
Fallacy | Description
false causation | the assumption that because two things happened together
column2: one caused the other

column1: false dichotomy | an argument that presents only two choices when more options exist
hasty generalization | a broad claim based on too few observations
slippery slope fallacy | the false assumption that a small first step will necessarily lead to extreme consequences
straw man | a misrepresentation of an opponent's position that makes it easier to argue against

column2: Ms. Stafford only claimed that students should be allowed to take statistics instead of algebra. She did not suggest that algebra is a useless subject. This illustrates a type of logical fallacy known as a straw man.

column1: A logical fallacy may present irrelevant information:
Fallacy | Description

appeal to nature | an argument that assumes the natural choice is always the best choice
bandwagon fallacy | an argument that assumes the popular choice is always the best choice
circular reasoning | an argument that supports a claim with the claim itself
guilt by association | an unfair negative association with another person or group that is intended to discredit someone or something
red herring | the use of a completely unrelated topic in support of a claim

Fallacy | Description
false causation | the assumption that because two things happened together

column1: Hint:
Lecture: Lines of latitude and lines of longitude are imaginary lines drawn on some globes and maps. They can help you find places on globes and maps.

Lines of latitude show how far north or south a place is. We use units called degrees to describe how far a place is from the equator. The equator is the line located at 0° latitude. We start counting degrees from there.
Lines north of the equator are labeled N for north. Lines south of the equator are labeled S for south. Lines of latitude are also called parallels because each line is parallel to the equator.

Lines of longitude are also called meridians. They show how far east or west a place is. We use degrees to help describe how far a place is from the prime meridian. The prime meridian is the line located at 0° longitude. Lines west of the prime meridian are labeled W. Lines east of the prime meridian are labeled E. Meridians meet at the north and south poles.
The equator goes all the way around the earth
column2: but the prime meridian is different. It only goes from the North Pole to the South Pole on one side of the earth. On the opposite side of the globe is another special meridian. It is labeled both 180°E and 180°W.

column1: Together
column2: lines of latitude and lines of longitude form a grid. You can use this grid to find the exact location of a place.

column1: Solution: The prime meridian is the line at 0° longitude. It intersects the Arctic Ocean. It does not intersect the Indian Ocean or the Pacific Ocean.

column1: 1517	"Question: Which of the following contains a vague pronoun reference?

column1: Hint:
Lecture: When writing
column2: make sure to avoid vague pronoun references. A vague pronoun reference occurs when a pronoun could refer to more than one possible antecedent.

column1: When Lisa and Kim finally landed
column2: she breathed a sigh of relief.

column1: The pronoun she could refer to either Lisa or Kim
column2: so the meaning of the sentence is unclear.

column1: Vague pronoun references can be corrected in one of two ways:
1. Replace the pronoun with its correct antecedent:
When Lisa and Kim finally landed
column2: Lisa breathed a sigh of relief.

column1: 2. Rewrite the sentence:
Lisa breathed a sigh of relief when she and Kim finally landed.
A vague pronoun reference also occurs when they
column2: them
column3: their
column5: it
column6: or its is used without its antecedent.

column1: They say that this nail polish dries in less than five minutes.
The pronoun they is used without its antecedent
column2: so the meaning of the sentence is unclear.

column1: This problem can be fixed by replacing the pronoun with its missing antecedent.
The advertisements say that this nail polish dries in less than five minutes.
Solution: The first answer choice contains a vague pronoun reference. The pronoun them could refer to the citizens or several competent city council members.
The citizens of Seaside have elected several competent city council members

column1: Hint: Read the passage. Then answer the question.

column1: In the canopy

column3: which helps the orchid spread its seeds to other branches.

column1: The orchid does not damage the tree it grows on
column2: but it also does not provide resources to the tree.

column1: Figure: epiphytic orchids growing on trees in a tropical forest.
Lecture: When two organisms of different species interact in a way that affects one or both organisms
column2: they form a symbiotic relationship. The word symbiosis comes from a Greek word that means living together. Scientists define types of symbiotic relationships based on how each organism is affected.

column1: This table lists three common types of symbiotic relationships. It shows how each organism is affected in each type of symbiotic relationship.
Type of symbiotic relationship | Organism of one species... | Organism of the other species...
Commensal | benefits | is not significantly affected
Mutualistic | benefits | benefits
Parasitic | benefits | is harmed (but not usually killed)
Solution: When an epiphytic orchid grows on a tree branch in the canopy
column2: the orchid gets more sunlight and wind than it would if it grew on the forest floor. So
column3: the orchid benefits from its relationship with the tree.

column1: The tree is not damaged by the orchid
column2: but the tree is not helped
column3: either. So
column4: the tree is not significantly affected by its relationship with the orchid.

column1: Since the orchid benefits and the tree is not significantly affected
column2: a commensal relationship is formed when an epiphytic orchid grows on a tree branch in the canopy.

""answer"": ""commensal""
""solution"": ""When an epiphytic orchid grows on a tree branch in the canopy
column2: the orchid benefits from more sunlight and wind
column3: which helps it perform more photosynthesis and spread its seeds. The tree is not damaged or significantly affected by the presence of the orchid. Therefore
column4: the relationship formed is a commensal relationship
column5: where one organism (the orchid) benefits

Distance tells you how far the object has moved. One unit used to measure distance is the kilometer.
Time tells you how long the object has spent moving. One unit used to measure time is the hour.
Think about two objects moving for the same amount of time. The object that is moving slower will go a shorter distance in that time. It is moving at a lower speed.

One speed walker moved 40 kilometers in 5 hours.
The other speed walker moved 45 kilometers in 5 hours.

column2: that speed walker must have moved at a lower speed.
